arXiv:2405.16239v1 Announce Type: new Abstract: We present new calculations of the leading-order one-loop amplitude and the decay rate for $H	o  ar{
u}
u \gamma$ within the standard model, employing reduction to a set of basic Passarino-Veltman functions resulting in a more concise expressions compared to prior works. Our result for the total decay rate is $\Gamma(H	o  ar{
u}
u \gamma)=1.33\,	ext{keV}$, in close agreement with the narrow width approximation (NWA) for the intermediate Z boson. We also provide a comparison with previous results available in the literature. We evaluate the differential decay rate and find that the non-resonant contributions from box diagrams beyond the NWA notably affect the off-shell kinematic region associated with high-energy photons, suggesting potential implications for dark sector mediators, particularly in future lepton collider experiments.

arXiv:2405.17341v1 Announce Type: new Abstract: We conduct a model-independent analysis of the distinct signatures of various generic new physics possibilities in the decay $B 	o K \, 
u \, \overline{
u}$ by analyzing the branching ratio as well as the missing mass-square distribution. Considering the final neutrinos to be of the same flavor with non-zero mass, we discuss the new physics contributions for both Dirac and Majorana neutrino possibilities. In our study, we utilize the analytical relations among form factors in semi-leptonic $B 	o K$ transitions, which are consistent with current lattice QCD predictions to a very high numerical accuracy. We provide constraints on different new physics parameters, taking into account the recent measurement of $B^+ 	o K^+ \, 
u \, \overline{
u}$ branching ratio by the Belle-II collaboration. In future, if the missing mass-square distribution for $B^+ 	o K^+ \, 
u \, \overline{
u}$ decay gets reported by Belle-II with analysis of more events than their present data set, one can not only investigate possible new physics effects in these decays, but also probe the Dirac/Majorana nature of the neutrinos using quantum statistics, since a difference between the two cases is known to exist in the presence of non-standard neutrino interactions.
